er/svg/98d19d47ccaae2f4027a94e0b7ca6c8434d7685e" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -2.005ex; width:18.598ex; height:5.676ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle m=
=3D{\frac {\Delta y}{\Delta x}}=3D\tan(\theta )}"></span></figcaption></fig=
ure>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics" title=3D"Mathem=
atics">mathematics</a>, the <b>slope</b> or <b>gradient</b> of a <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Line_(mathematics)" class=3D"mw-redirect" ti=
tle=3D"Line (mathematics)">line</a> is a number that describes the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Direction_(geometry)" title=3D"Direction =
(geometry)">direction</a> of the line on a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Plane_(geometry)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Plane (geometry)"=
>plane</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slope#cite_note-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Often denoted by the lett=
er <i>m</i>, slope is calculated as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Ratio" title=3D"Ratio">ratio</a> of the vertical change to the horizo=
ntal change ("rise over run") between two distinct points on the line, givi=
ng the same A slope is the ratio of the vertical distance (rise) to the hor=
izontal distance (run) between two points, not a direct distance or a direc=
t angle for any choice of points. To explain, a slope is the <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ratio" title=3D"Ratio">ratio</a> of the vertical=
 distance (rise) to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Horizontal=
_plane" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Horizontal plane">horizontal</a> dis=
tance (run) between two points, not a direct <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Distance" title=3D"Distance">distance</a> or a direct <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Angle" title=3D"Angle">angle</a>
The line may be physical =E2=80=93 as set by a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Surveying" title=3D"Surveying">road surveyor</a>, pictorial as=
 in a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diagram" title=3D"Diagram">d=
iagram</a> of a road or roof, or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P=
ure_mathematics" title=3D"Pure mathematics">abstract</a>.
An application of the mathematical concept is found in the <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grade_(slope)" title=3D"Grade (slope)">grade</a> o=
r <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gradient" title=3D"Gradient">gra=
dient</a> in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geography" title=3D"G=
eography">geography</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Civil_=
engineering" title=3D"Civil engineering">civil engineering</a>.=20
</p><p>The <i>steepness</i>, incline, or grade of a line is the <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Absolute_value" title=3D"Absolute value">abso=
lute value</a> of its slope: greater absolute value indicates a steeper lin=
e. The line trend is defined as follows:=20
</p>
<ul><li>An "increasing" or "ascending" line goes <em>up</em> from left to r=
ight and has positive slope: <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-eleme=
nt-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" styl=
e=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alt=
text=3D"{\displaystyle m&gt;0}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
