  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/bb86068f5f3d47b01a0face3182fb6bff72f68d0" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -2.171ex; width:21.43ex; height:5.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle m=
=3D{\frac {\Delta y}{\Delta x}}=3D{\frac {y_{2}-y_{1}}{x_{2}-x_{1}}}.}"></s=
pan></dd></dl>
<p>Through <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trigonometry" title=3D"=
Trigonometry">trigonometry</a>, the slope <i>m</i> of a line is related to =
its <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Angle" title=3D"Angle">angle</=
a> of inclination <i>=CE=B8</i> by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Tangent_function" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Tangent function">tan=
gent function</a>
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e m=3D\tan(\theta ).}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>m</mi>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mi>tan</mi>
        <mo>=E2=81=A1<!-- =E2=81=A1 --></mo>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mi>=CE=B8<!-- =CE=B8 --></mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
        <mo>.</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle m=3D\tan(\the=
ta ).}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/d8f7b32a590071b56cd36c4b5fe7f32e8f75978e" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.838ex; width:12.045ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle m=
=3D\tan(\theta ).}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>Thus, a 45=C2=B0 rising line has slope <i>m =3D</i> +1, and a 45=C2=B0 f=
alling line has slope <i>m =3D</i> =E2=88=921.
</p><p>Generalizing this, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Differen=
tial_calculus" title=3D"Differential calculus">differential calculus</a> de=
fines the slope of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plane_curve" =
title=3D"Plane curve">plane curve</a> at a point as the slope of its <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tangent" title=3D"Tangent">tangent line<=
/a> at that point. When the curve is approximated by a series of points, th=
e slope of the curve may be approximated by the slope of the <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Secant_line" title=3D"Secant line">secant line</=
a> between two nearby points. When the curve is given as the graph of an <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebraic_expression" title=3D"Algeb=
raic expression">algebraic expression</a>, calculus gives <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Derivative" title=3D"Derivative">formulas for the s=
lope</a> at each point. Slope is thus one of the central ideas of calculus =
and its applications to design.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Notation">Notation</h2><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSlope&amp;action=3De=
dit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Notation"><span>edit</span></a>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>There seems to be no clear answer as to why the letter <i>m</i> is used =
for slope, but it first appears in English in <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Matthew_O%27Brien_(mathematician)" title=3D"Matthew O'Brien (ma=
thematician)">O'Brien</a> (1844)<sup id=3D"cite_ref-2" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slope#cite_note-2"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> who =
introduced the equation of a line as <span class=3D"nowrap">"<i>y</i> =3D <=
i>mx</i> + <i>b</i>"</span>, and it can also be found in <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isaac_Todhunter" title=3D"Isaac Todhunter">Todhunter=
</a> (1888)<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slope#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> who wrote "<i>y</i> =3D <=
i>mx</i> + <i>c</i>".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slope#cite_note-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Definition">Definition</h2>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSlope&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Definition"><span>edit</spa=
n></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Slope_of_lines_illustrated.jpg" class=3D"mw-f=
ile-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons=
