dit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit section: Calculus"><span>edit</span></a>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Frame"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Tangent_function_animation.gif" class=3D"mw-f=
ile-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons=
/2/2d/Tangent_function_animation.gif" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"300" heig=
ht=3D"285" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"300" data-file-heig=
ht=3D"285"></a><figcaption>At each point, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Derivative" title=3D"Derivative">derivative</a> is the slope of=
 a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Line_(geometry)" title=3D"Line =
(geometry)">line</a> that is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tange=
nt" title=3D"Tangent">tangent</a> to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Curve" title=3D"Curve">curve</a> at that point. Note: the derivative=
 at point A is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Positive_number" cl=
ass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Positive number">positive</a> where green and =
dash=E2=80=93dot, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Negative_number"=
 title=3D"Negative number">negative</a> where red and dashed, and <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zero_(number)" class=3D"mw-redirect" titl=
e=3D"Zero (number)">zero</a> where black and solid.</figcaption></figure>
<p>The concept of a slope is central to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Differential_calculus" title=3D"Differential calculus">differential c=
alculus</a>. For non-linear functions, the rate of change varies along the =
curve. The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Derivative" title=3D"De=
rivative">derivative</a> of the function at a point is the slope of the lin=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tangent" title=3D"Tangent">tange=
nt</a> to the curve at the point and is thus equal to the rate of change of=
 the function at that point.
</p><p>If we let =CE=94<i>x</i> and =CE=94<i>y</i> be the distances (along =
the <i>x</i> and <i>y</i> axes, respectively) between two points on a curve=
, then the slope given by the above definition,
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e m=3D{\frac {\Delta y}{\Delta x}}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
