          <mfrac>
            <mrow>
              <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">=CE=94<!-- =CE=94 --></mi>
              <mi>y</mi>
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">=CE=94<!-- =CE=94 --></mi>
              <mi>x</mi>
            </mrow>
          </mfrac>
        </mrow>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle m=3D{\frac {\=
Delta y}{\Delta x}}}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/5a20d2a034e0b9063b50df5ce9876dd5b9734162" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -2.005ex; width:9.241ex; height:5.676ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle m=
=3D{\frac {\Delta y}{\Delta x}}}"></span>,</dd></dl>
<p>is the slope of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Secant_line" =
title=3D"Secant line">secant line</a> to the curve. For a line, the secant =
between any two points is the line itself, but this is not the case for any=
 other type of curve.
</p><p>For example, the slope of the secant intersecting <i>y</i> =3D <i>x<=
/i><sup>2</sup> at (0,0) and (3,9) is 3. (The slope of the tangent at <span=
 class=3D"nowrap"><i>x</i> =3D <span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"num">3</=
span>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"den">2</span></span></span> is also 3&nbsp;=E2=
=88=92&nbsp;<i>a</i> consequence of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Mean_value_theorem" title=3D"Mean value theorem">mean value theorem</=
a>.)
</p><p>By moving the two points closer together so that =CE=94<i>y</i> and =
=CE=94<i>x</i> decrease, the secant line more closely approximates a tangen=
t line to the curve, and as such the slope of the secant approaches that of=
 the tangent. Using <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Differential_c=
alculus" title=3D"Differential calculus">differential calculus</a>, we can =
determine the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Limit_of_a_function"=
 title=3D"Limit of a function">limit</a>, or the value that =CE=94<i>y</i>/=
=CE=94<i>x</i> approaches as =CE=94<i>y</i> and =CE=94<i>x</i> get closer t=
o <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zero" class=3D"mw-redirect" titl=
e=3D"Zero">zero</a>; it follows that this limit is the exact slope of the t=
angent. If <i>y</i> is dependent on <i>x</i>, then it is sufficient to take=
 the limit where only =CE=94<i>x</i> approaches zero. Therefore, the slope =
