}"></span> of slopes is the same before and after the shear. This invarianc=
e of slope differences makes slope an angular <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Invariant_measure" title=3D"Invariant measure">invariant measur=
e</a>, on a par with circular angle (invariant under rotation) and hyperbol=
ic angle, with invariance group of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Squeeze_mapping" title=3D"Squeeze mapping">squeeze mappings</a>.<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-7" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/S=
lope#cite_note-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-8" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slope#cite_note-8"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Slope_(pitch)_of_a_roof"><s=
pan id=3D"Slope_.28pitch.29_of_a_roof"></span>Slope (pitch) of a roof</h2><=
span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</spa=
n><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSlope&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D9" title=3D"Edit section: Slope (pitch) of a roof"><s=
pan>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></=
div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roof_pitch" title=3D=
"Roof pitch">Roof pitch</a></div>
<p>The slope of a roof, traditionally and commonly called the <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roof_pitch" title=3D"Roof pitch">roof pitch</a>=
, in carpentry and architecture in the US is commonly described in terms of=
 integer fractions of one foot (geometric tangent, rise over run), a legacy=
 of British imperial measure. Other units are in use in other locales, with=
 similar conventions. For details, see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Roof_pitch" title=3D"Roof pitch">roof pitch</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Slope_of_a_road_or_railway"=
>Slope of a road or railway</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/i=
ndex.php?title=3DSlope&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D10" title=3D"Edit se=
ction: Slope of a road or railway"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-e=
ditsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main articles: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grade_(slope)" titl=
e=3D"Grade (slope)">Grade (slope)</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Grade_separation" title=3D"Grade separation">Grade separation</a></=
div>
<p>There are two common ways to describe the steepness of a <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Road" title=3D"Road">road</a> or <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rail_tracks" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Rail t=
racks">railroad</a>. One is by the angle between 0=C2=B0 and 90=C2=B0 (in d=
egrees), and the other is by the slope in a percentage. See also <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Steep_grade_railway" title=3D"Steep grade ra=
ilway">steep grade railway</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Rack_railway" title=3D"Rack railway">rack railway</a>.
</p><p>The formulae for converting a slope given as a percentage into an an=
gle in degrees and vice versa are:=20
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e {\text{angle}}=3D\arctan \left({\frac {\text{slope}}{100\%}}\right)}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mtext>angle</mtext>
        </mrow>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mi>arctan</mi>
        <mo>=E2=81=A1<!-- =E2=81=A1 --></mo>
        <mrow>
          <mo>(</mo>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mfrac>
              <mtext>slope</mtext>
              <mrow>
                <mn>100</mn>
                <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">%<!-- % --></mi>
              </mrow>
            </mfrac>
          </mrow>
          <mo>)</mo>
        </mrow>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle {\text{angle}=
}=3D\arctan \left({\frac {\text{slope}}{100\%}}\right)}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/83cdbb8efc8a1a4907bda9c8c38a698e9572660b" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -2.505ex; width:24.542ex; height:6.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle {\=
text{angle}}=3D\arctan \left({\frac {\text{slope}}{100\%}}\right)}"></span>=
 (this is the inverse function of tangent; see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Trigonometry" title=3D"Trigonometry">trigonometry</a>)</dd></d=
l>
<p>and
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e {\mbox{slope}}=3D100\%\times \tan({\mbox{angle}}),}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mstyle displaystyle=3D"false" scriptlevel=3D"0">
            <mtext>slope</mtext>
          </mstyle>
        </mrow>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mn>100</mn>
        <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">%<!-- % --></mi>
        <mo>=C3=97<!-- =C3=97 --></mo>
        <mi>tan</mi>
        <mo>=E2=81=A1<!-- =E2=81=A1 --></mo>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mstyle displaystyle=3D"false" scriptlevel=3D"0">
            <mtext>angle</mtext>
          </mstyle>
        </mrow>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
        <mo>,</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle {\mbox{slope}=
}=3D100\%\times \tan({\mbox{angle}}),}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/e1d7358a713937f07df143c8947c9ac4512409d4" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.838ex; width:27.525ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle {\=
mbox{slope}}=3D100\%\times \tan({\mbox{angle}}),}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>where <i>angle</i> is in degrees and the trigonometric functions operate=
 in degrees. For example, a slope of 100<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Percent_sign" title=3D"Percent sign">%</a> or 1000<a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Per_mil" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Per mil">=E2=
=80=B0</a> is an angle of 45=C2=B0.
</p><p>A third way is to give one unit of rise in say 10, 20, 50 or 100 hor=
izontal units, e.g. 1:10. 1:20, 1:50 or 1:100 (or "1 <i>in</i> 10", "1 <i>i=
n</i> 20", etc.) 1:10 is steeper than 1:20. For example, steepness of 20% m=
eans 1:5 or an incline with angle 11.3=C2=B0.
</p><p>Roads and railways have both longitudinal slopes and cross slopes.
</p>
